Or maybe adjust to 1-based in Fortran. This is a critical part. Let's see: Original Java code:

int a = Integer.parseInt(sc.next()) - 1;
int b = Integer.parseInt(sc.next()) - 1;

So the input is 1-based, and the code converts to 0-based. So in Fortran, perhaps nodes are 0-based as well. But Fortran arrays are 1-based by default, but can be 0-based if specified. So perhaps in Fortran, the code will use 0-based indices for nodes. So when reading a and b, subtract 1, then store in the adjacency list. But in Fortran, handling 0-based arrays can be done by specifying the lower bound.
